00:34:37.560 --> 00:34:41.500
This is a little bit — so, I don't know why I'm thinking about it this way.

00:34:41.500 --> 00:34:44.940
I don't think it's remotely correct.

00:34:45.300 --> 00:34:54.680
But, like, what if polytheism refers to, like, historical trajectory, not one – so, like, you were saying, John,

00:34:55.180 --> 00:35:01.500
it feels like everybody – there's all these different sects, but they're all a version of monolingualism or monotheism.

00:35:01.500 --> 00:35:02.700
Oh, Jesus, monotheism.

00:35:02.700 --> 00:35:03.040
Right.

00:35:04.320 --> 00:35:11.680
What if polytheism is just a condition of possibility for the elaboration of several different monotheisms?

00:35:11.880 --> 00:35:19.640
Like, so, like, you go along, you're trudging along in one kind of paradigm, and then somebody like Nietzsche comes along and reorganizes it.

00:35:19.820 --> 00:35:28.500
But then it just kind of splits off, and there's multiple – there's always just multiple monotheisms, at least in the general.

00:35:28.500 --> 00:35:48.740
But that's – I mean, I think that that's right, because, for instance, like, I have a very good friend who is a pastor of Christianity, and she, you know, does – she constantly wants to distance herself from the Christianity of the evangelicals and the Christianity – you know, in other words, the point being, Christianity is not itself one thing, right?

00:35:48.740 --> 00:35:51.800
Like, it is, of course, heterogeneous.

00:35:52.300 --> 00:36:15.560
But nevertheless, like, I still have this thing, and maybe this returns to a question that I would want to put to why he is so interested in polytheism is because, to me, the problem is once – whenever you bring in transcendence, like, whenever you bring in an otherworldly justification or explanation for an action, for a morality, for a belief, or whatever,

00:36:16.700 --> 00:36:19.860
you introduce the problem, right?

00:36:19.940 --> 00:36:26.320
Like, to me, you introduce – it's a power move that is unassailable, right?

00:36:26.440 --> 00:36:33.360
Like, it's – I mean, one can disagree with that god or whatever, but it's like, man, fucking god said this.

00:36:33.460 --> 00:36:38.160
Like, you introduce an unassailable power, transcendent power position.

00:36:38.880 --> 00:36:46.420
Whether that's done polytheistically or not, like, I mean, I believe that there is – I believe that there is a difference, and I take your point in terms of the Zeus thing.

00:36:46.520 --> 00:36:48.500
I think that that – I think that that is right.

00:36:48.500 --> 00:36:53.500
But it actually seems to me as if everyone's always trying to invent monotheisms.

00:36:54.200 --> 00:37:04.400
It's just that sometimes they don't take, maybe, at some historical moments, and then we call it polytheism.

00:37:04.880 --> 00:37:05.860
You know what I mean?

00:37:06.900 --> 00:37:08.760
Like, so polytheism isn't a thing.

00:37:08.960 --> 00:37:10.500
It's just a failure.

00:37:10.740 --> 00:37:12.000
Maybe that's what his claim is here.

00:37:12.080 --> 00:37:12.320
I don't know.

00:37:12.320 --> 00:37:17.860
But I – but yeah, I mean, I think so because, like, look, he says, like, Plato trying to start a religion.

00:37:18.220 --> 00:37:20.100
Pythagoras trying to start a religion, right?

00:37:20.240 --> 00:37:20.400
Yeah.

00:37:20.540 --> 00:37:25.440
But it's not a – but it doesn't reveal much about them so much as it –

00:37:25.440 --> 00:37:27.440
The cultural conditions in which they're –

00:37:27.440 --> 00:37:28.460
The cultural conditions.

00:37:28.460 --> 00:37:31.120
So it's like, yeah, it's going to take root in some people.

00:37:31.180 --> 00:37:39.560
But I think the other thing that really matters is what is the instinctive orientation to difference from the people in which it takes hold of?

00:37:39.920 --> 00:37:53.840
If it is the transcendent position of mine is right and yours is wrong, not just mine is mine and yours is yours, then it is just struggling monotheisms because it's me against the world or us against the world.

00:37:54.880 --> 00:38:16.040
If the orientation is, like, yeah, I got my thing and you got your thing and sometimes they butt heads and sometimes they create friction between each other and sometimes they have nothing to do with each other and the orientation is one of agonism rather than antagonism and especially truth and falsity, then, like, that's the difference in the orientation.

00:38:16.600 --> 00:38:24.920
So, you know, I mean – and there's also, like, the imperial – we're talking about an imperial – monotheism is an imperial impulse, right?

00:38:24.980 --> 00:38:31.780
And we look at, like, our own contemporary moment and it feels like a different kind of war.

00:38:31.880 --> 00:38:40.660
It is a war of imperialism and colonization, not a war of the expulsion of strength or the expression of strength, right?

00:38:41.340 --> 00:38:57.100
Like, which I think, you know, is another way – he's, like, you know, I think polytheism for him is the war of the expression of power rather than that of territorializing, dominating, colonizing, extraction of resource sort of thing.

00:38:57.100 --> 00:39:22.600
Like, you know, one is – to bring it to the dice roll thing, monotheism, imperialism is the playing the game, playing the odds, playing to win, whereas polytheism is a matter of just the simple – like, is just simply playing the game.

00:39:26.740 --> 00:39:36.980
The thing that's just sort of popping in the back of my mind is that, you know, and this is a line of his from, what, Birth of Tragedy, probably?

00:39:37.760 --> 00:39:47.700
But Rome versus Judea, which is polytheism versus monotheism, you know?

00:39:48.800 --> 00:39:52.460
And it's clear who won, right?

00:39:52.620 --> 00:39:58.180
Like, it's, you know, monotheism – like, the papacy is in Rome, right?

00:39:58.340 --> 00:40:03.040
Like, it's clear who won that battle.

00:40:03.620 --> 00:40:07.540
And, I mean, I don't know.

00:40:07.700 --> 00:40:15.260
I still increasingly am feeling like polytheism is not a condition so much as it's just the absence of a dominant monotheism.

00:40:16.160 --> 00:40:21.460
Well, except for – well, Rome, because I usually hear that – you know, I do remember that one.

00:40:21.540 --> 00:40:25.960
But, you know, like the – like Saint – was it – not Jeremias, what's his name?

00:40:26.860 --> 00:40:27.260
Jerome.

00:40:27.380 --> 00:40:32.000
Saint Jerome says, you know, like, what does Athens have to do with Jerusalem?

00:40:33.260 --> 00:40:37.500
And, you know, like, there again, like polytheism, you know, against –

00:40:37.500 --> 00:40:38.180
Right, right, right.

00:40:38.420 --> 00:40:43.120
Except for Rome is an interesting wrinkle to that narrative because –

00:40:43.120 --> 00:40:45.140
It's imperial power.

00:40:45.660 --> 00:40:46.900
Exactly, right?

00:40:46.960 --> 00:40:54.060
Because, like, Judaic monotheism was, you know, quite regional and unimportant for a very long time.

00:40:54.680 --> 00:40:58.520
And it's not the polytheism of Rome that really matters.

00:40:58.800 --> 00:41:03.300
It's the – it's the monotheistic imperialism, right?

00:41:03.360 --> 00:41:10.700
So it's like secular – like, mono – like, secular imperialism meets religious monotheism.

00:41:10.860 --> 00:41:13.760
Like, that was the great atom bomb of Christianity.

00:41:14.980 --> 00:41:21.140
I think it would be – that's one of those – like, I know so little of Roman history.

00:41:21.640 --> 00:41:21.800
Yeah.

00:41:21.900 --> 00:41:23.480
You know, I think that's a really interesting time.

00:41:23.580 --> 00:41:27.600
It was 400 – like, before Constantine – like, so, okay, we can say with Constantine,

00:41:27.860 --> 00:41:33.820
Christianity becomes the imperial religion and then European history sort of starts, right?

00:41:33.900 --> 00:41:34.420
Like – but, like –

00:41:34.420 --> 00:41:34.520
Yeah.

00:41:35.840 --> 00:41:39.300
Prior to that, I mean, the – I don't know enough about it.

00:41:39.300 --> 00:41:46.920
But I imagine that's just an incredibly fascinating time to think, like, how did religion actually operate for those few hundred years, right?

00:41:46.980 --> 00:41:48.060
Like, I mean –

00:41:48.060 --> 00:41:49.520
It was incredibly heterogeneous.

00:41:49.560 --> 00:41:49.920
What was it?

00:41:50.180 --> 00:41:51.100
Well, that's what I'm wondering.

00:41:51.260 --> 00:42:01.360
Like, was it, in fact, that – I mean, because, I mean, I just – you know, when you find the ruins, it's always like, here's a temple to this person and a temple to that person and a temple to that – or this god or that god or the other god.

00:42:01.560 --> 00:42:03.360
It's one of my favorite periods of history.

00:42:03.720 --> 00:42:06.640
People were adherents of this thing and not that thing, and, yeah.

00:42:07.580 --> 00:42:23.680
Right, but, again, like, you know, and, I mean, I think even Paul mentions this in the letter to the Corinthians, but he's, like – he's making fun of polytheism and, you know, he makes fun of – you know, they have all the different statues and you have to make sacrifices to all of the different gods.

00:42:24.000 --> 00:42:27.380
And then there's the statue of the unknown god, just in case you forgot one.

00:42:28.080 --> 00:42:34.580
And, you know, it's like – and the comic relief is like, well, if you just have the right god, then you know what to deal with.

00:42:34.580 --> 00:42:50.120
But, you know, here is a – you know, one is operating within a world of the unknowable, like, you know, we're on the stage for the gods, and the gods have us for their stage and their own drama going on.

00:42:50.200 --> 00:42:54.000
So there's not a one-to-one cohesive, like, disconnect.

00:42:54.140 --> 00:42:56.040
Like, it is far more chaotic.

00:42:56.440 --> 00:43:03.760
And, like, this is very much so true within the Roman context as well, especially because, you know, Rome is so imperial.

00:43:04.540 --> 00:43:14.080
It's – it has – and its policies are maybe not as liberal as those of ancient Persia, which were just, like, laissez-faire, like, worship whoever you want.

00:43:15.040 --> 00:43:19.540
But it was very sort of, like, keep your regional gods, you know, do your thing.

00:43:20.460 --> 00:43:30.920
And it was, in some ways, a policy of tolerance, like, we're not going to change your religion so long as you acknowledge –

00:43:30.920 --> 00:43:31.800
You pay your taxes.

00:43:32.300 --> 00:43:33.440
As long as you pay your taxes.

00:43:33.540 --> 00:43:37.020
As long as you acknowledge Rome as your – you know, your secular god.

00:43:37.020 --> 00:43:44.540
Or at least – and oftentimes – and this is the big thing that was the problematic for monotheistic religions is, you know, keep your own gods.

00:43:44.840 --> 00:43:46.940
Just include ours, too, right?

00:43:47.060 --> 00:43:48.820
Like, ours make your docket.

00:43:49.160 --> 00:43:53.300
And this is obviously not tolerable for a monotheistic culture.

00:43:53.880 --> 00:44:04.160
But what was monotheistic about it was, I mean, the infrastructure, the language, the architecture, right?

00:44:04.160 --> 00:44:05.840
Even just the architecture of the thing.

00:44:05.840 --> 00:44:13.480
I mean, like, Latinitas is the sort of the imperial tool rather than religion.

00:44:13.880 --> 00:44:28.760
But, you know, it's like – so, in many ways, I always see Rome as the great creator of infrastructure that almost any idea can parasitically infect.

00:44:28.980 --> 00:44:40.540
It just so happened to be, you know, a particular sect of Judaism that just, like, found itself coursing throughout all of the material infrastructure of Rome.

00:44:40.540 --> 00:44:52.000
And, you know, it just tapped that imperial, like, like, monotheism, like, monotheism, like, imperialism, and just inflected it religiously.

00:44:52.720 --> 00:45:04.820
It's like – that's – that's why, you know, it can't just be mono – like, when I hear monotheism there, I don't hear strictly religion, like, in terms of religion.

00:45:04.820 --> 00:45:07.380
When I hear polytheism, I don't hear strictly religion either.

00:45:07.380 --> 00:45:07.580
Right.

00:45:07.580 --> 00:45:07.860
Right.

00:45:07.860 --> 00:45:08.720
I understand that.

00:45:08.720 --> 00:45:09.080
Yeah.

00:45:11.780 --> 00:45:16.160
I wasn't really thinking of religion exclusively at all with that.

00:45:16.160 --> 00:45:19.000
I was thinking of, like, forms of thought, right?

00:45:19.100 --> 00:45:31.140
I mean, that's—Nietzsche's thing is that pretty much every line of thinking is susceptible to a theistic logic or a theological structure, right?

00:45:31.220 --> 00:45:32.940
I mean, science is susceptible.

00:45:33.540 --> 00:45:34.660
The arts are susceptible.

00:45:35.160 --> 00:45:39.940
Well, what is science without Christianity and Rome, right?

00:45:39.940 --> 00:45:41.680
Could science even exist?

00:45:41.860 --> 00:45:52.140
Because it has to be predicated on an elusive real world that we are not capable of accessing except through a very particular methodology.

00:45:52.700 --> 00:45:56.320
And it is monotheistic in that that one truth is the case.

00:45:56.860 --> 00:46:07.740
And it's imperial and it's sort of—and it's justification for the use of power to impose that empirical reality on everything else.

00:46:08.340 --> 00:46:11.080
One of the—I forget which—

00:46:11.080 --> 00:46:14.520
Which produces concepts just in a—on a highway.

00:46:15.540 --> 00:46:24.940
He takes down the potential arrogance of science in a very short section where he basically says that—

00:46:24.940 --> 00:46:31.960
that they're—basically we've gotten better at describing things with precision.

00:46:31.960 --> 00:46:36.880
But we still have no explanation of literally—like, where did life come from?

00:46:37.000 --> 00:46:39.420
How did chemical processes come about?

00:46:39.740 --> 00:46:41.340
We can describe them in increasing detail.

00:46:41.340 --> 00:46:43.540
How does cause actually relate to it?

00:46:43.540 --> 00:46:45.380
What is the cause and what is an effect?

00:46:45.400 --> 00:46:49.540
But we have no sense of origin or cause or causality still.

00:46:50.100 --> 00:46:54.520
Like, that's still true since Nietzsche had, like, wrote that.

00:46:54.600 --> 00:46:55.720
That's still true today.

00:46:56.220 --> 00:47:04.620
You know, so we had, like, science—but then again, like, I don't think modern science claims to really do anything else besides describe shit either.

00:47:05.360 --> 00:47:05.620
Right?

00:47:05.680 --> 00:47:08.180
I mean, it's like—maybe back then it did.

00:47:08.520 --> 00:47:10.960
But, like, not—when I think of, like, how science—

00:47:10.960 --> 00:47:14.820
If it gets into political and cultural policy and practice, then it does.

00:47:15.260 --> 00:47:17.640
And science becomes the substantiating force for then.

00:47:18.000 --> 00:47:19.500
You know, because, like, you read most scientific papers.

00:47:19.600 --> 00:47:22.460
Like, all right, well, you know, there's a correlation between X and Y.

00:47:22.560 --> 00:47:24.200
And here's the significance of that correlation.

00:47:24.460 --> 00:47:26.980
And it's not making a cause-effect claim.

00:47:27.140 --> 00:47:35.260
It's imagining probabilities, possibilities, like, distance between, effectively, descriptions.

00:47:35.420 --> 00:47:36.280
Like, here's one description.

00:47:36.420 --> 00:47:37.300
Here's another description.

00:47:37.300 --> 00:47:42.580
Those two descriptions just so happen to come, you know, paired up quite often.

00:47:43.200 --> 00:47:46.620
But then once it gets translated into, now what do we do with this?

00:47:46.680 --> 00:47:53.680
Now it's like, because of, you know, these scientific facts, now we act, you know, in this sort of way.

00:47:53.820 --> 00:47:56.420
And it is completely monotheistic.

00:47:57.940 --> 00:47:58.380
Yeah.

00:47:59.100 --> 00:48:00.240
Although—

00:48:00.240 --> 00:48:01.180
Here's the truth following.

00:48:01.280 --> 00:48:01.980
Oh, yeah.

00:48:02.860 --> 00:48:04.300
Were you going to say something, John?

00:48:04.440 --> 00:48:06.860
Yeah, I mean, I'm more of a fan of science.

00:48:07.200 --> 00:48:08.280
Oh, I like science.

00:48:09.260 --> 00:48:19.980
I want to take it in as somewhat – because, you know, one of the things that – whether – I just find it hard to think of science as monotheistic in that regard.

00:48:21.860 --> 00:48:26.480
I get the idea of there being one truth, like, it's either this or it's that.

00:48:26.560 --> 00:48:38.460
But I also feel like in the last, I don't know, 50, 60 years, there's just enough stuff coming out of, whether it's theoretical physics or computational, you know, like, that doesn't really think that, right?

00:48:38.540 --> 00:48:39.200
Like, that we –

00:48:39.200 --> 00:48:39.860
On the fringe.

00:48:41.140 --> 00:48:43.760
Well, I don't know if it's – I don't know if it's the fringe.

00:48:43.940 --> 00:48:50.980
I mean, I actually, you know, like – I grant that it's not generalized, right?

00:48:51.060 --> 00:48:53.860
Like, it's not some massive majority at all.

00:48:53.920 --> 00:48:56.600
But I do feel like these are – they're really important.

00:48:57.600 --> 00:49:01.100
Oh, I think it's – I think even the monotheistic stuff is important.

00:49:01.440 --> 00:49:02.480
Like, you know, don't get me wrong.

00:49:02.540 --> 00:49:05.600
I don't think that is – like, we need to rebel against it.

00:49:05.660 --> 00:49:20.740
Like, I mean, here – like, the pandemic was a good – is a good example for that sort of, like, monotheistic imperialism taking hold is that, you know, the scientific operation multiplied the pandemic and possible responses to it.

00:49:20.740 --> 00:49:37.360
And the cultural legislative orientation to it was to narrow it, was to – and what was interesting to me – because I think narrowing it and making it actionable was the right move, right?

00:49:37.420 --> 00:49:41.380
Like, because there needs to be some kind of, like, to have a strategy.

00:49:41.640 --> 00:49:42.160
We need a program.

00:49:42.160 --> 00:49:43.940
There has to be some kind of coherence, right?

00:49:44.140 --> 00:49:48.180
But that was never the justification for why we're all doing this thing, right?

00:49:48.180 --> 00:49:51.600
It was never like, look, there are a lot of different things that we could do.

00:49:52.500 --> 00:49:53.400
All of them may work.

00:49:53.520 --> 00:49:54.400
None of them may work.

00:49:54.660 --> 00:49:55.080
But whatever it is –

00:49:55.080 --> 00:49:57.220
We're just going to arbitrarily pick this thing.

00:49:57.240 --> 00:49:59.120
Yeah, we're going to choose this one, and here's the deal.

00:49:59.400 --> 00:50:01.040
We have to do it, right?

00:50:01.040 --> 00:50:02.400
We all have to do it, right?

00:50:02.680 --> 00:50:08.240
That wasn't – you know, like, for obvious reasons, that wasn't the rationale, even though that's effectively what we were doing.

00:50:08.640 --> 00:50:17.760
And instead it was, this is the obvious, undeniable, right way of doing it, and if you don't do it, you're a science-denying cuckoo head.

00:50:18.180 --> 00:50:25.140
But then how often those absolutes change day to day, even, like, within an hour, you'd have a new thing that you absolutely must do.

00:50:25.560 --> 00:50:37.700
But this is why the non-scientific cuckoo heads, like, they were given life, because they're like, well, I can measure inconsistencies, and we used to have to do this thing, and you were stupid if you didn't do it.

00:50:37.820 --> 00:50:41.900
And now you have to do this thing in 180 degrees, and you're stupid if you don't do it.

00:50:42.980 --> 00:50:44.580
So they don't know what the fuck they're doing.

00:50:44.900 --> 00:50:49.840
So they don't know what they're doing, and they think the whole thing is a joke, and the whole line of conspiracy theories comes out.

00:50:50.300 --> 00:51:01.240
And I was like, you know, I don't think there's a good option there, because our primary mechanism for coercing behavior is to accord it with the truth and a knowledge system.

00:51:01.500 --> 00:51:11.620
And there's just no way that saying, well, we're going to experiment with something, and the only thing that we feel pretty comfortable with is that we all have to be on the same page with this experiment.

00:51:11.980 --> 00:51:14.220
Like, that wasn't going to work at all.

00:51:14.380 --> 00:51:14.480
Yeah.

00:51:14.800 --> 00:51:20.640
So that, well, it's true, and if you're a psycho, if you don't do it, that maybe had the next best shot of working.

00:51:21.780 --> 00:51:25.400
And it worked mostly, kind of, but.

00:51:25.600 --> 00:51:30.720
Well, I guess the stakes were so high, the stakes were so high that provisionality was not an option.

00:51:30.940 --> 00:51:36.580
There's no way the CDC could have just been like, maybe we should do this, and you could try this out.

00:51:36.680 --> 00:51:40.740
Like, there's no way in their policies that they could frame it in that kind of language.

00:51:40.740 --> 00:51:42.480
So it had to be framed.

00:51:42.820 --> 00:51:47.440
As soon as they got the information, they had to push it out there as, like, this is what we do now.

00:51:47.820 --> 00:51:49.060
Now we wash our groceries.

00:51:49.720 --> 00:51:52.000
We rinse off our grocery bags, right?

00:51:52.060 --> 00:52:01.800
And then it's like, and then, so the distance between provisionality and absolutes collapsed and created absolute chaos politically.

00:52:01.940 --> 00:52:05.620
Well, think about, like, how, like, washing, like, we all wash our groceries now.

00:52:05.720 --> 00:52:09.560
Think about the variety of ways in which that disseminates, right?

00:52:09.560 --> 00:52:19.540
There are the pious who are like, yes, we religiously wash our groceries because it is true and right and holy be thy banana washer, right?

00:52:19.700 --> 00:52:31.400
And then there are the heterodox who are like, this is government conspiracy, you know, they want us to wash out the evidence that this is how they're planting chips in the brains, right?

00:52:31.680 --> 00:52:37.900
And then there are the people who I would think were in this camp are like, okay, well, this is provisional, right?

00:52:37.980 --> 00:52:45.240
Like, given sort of, like, what's going on, this does seem to have the best momentary chance of sort of slowing down the spread of this thing.

00:52:45.360 --> 00:52:52.860
So, cool, I'll wash my vegetables now and then I'll be okay with it if it changes next week.

00:52:53.140 --> 00:52:56.500
I just think that third category is very, very small.

00:52:57.200 --> 00:53:02.060
Yeah, I think that was rare because, yeah, I mean, it just, I mean, everybody, it polarized people.

00:53:02.060 --> 00:53:04.420
That's why it turned into a, but it turned into a holy world.

00:53:04.420 --> 00:53:10.220
But that's, so that's partly what I'm saying about the polytheism question is that I don't think that polytheism is actually a thing.

00:53:10.340 --> 00:53:15.960
It is just a situation in which no particular monotheism has dominated yet, right?

00:53:16.000 --> 00:53:24.520
Like, in other words, it's not, you know, so that this is the case here is that you have the pious story, the pious counter story.

00:53:24.900 --> 00:53:32.060
Neither one works, but I mean, that's, that's how I hear what you're saying is that polytheism, there aren't polytheisms.

